2. Kubernetes Architecture?
Control plane (Master Node) API SERVER, KUBE SCHEDULER, ETCD, CONTROLLER MANAGER
Data plane (Worked Node) KUBELET, KUBE PROXY, CONTAINER RUNTIME

KUBELET: Create pod, check status of pod, inform API SERVER about the pod status.
KUBE PROXY: IP address to pod will be allocated by the Kube Proxy, acts as a load balancer to the pod
CONTAINER RUNTIME: Container runtime is required to start the container. Docker shim is the container runtime which is used by Kubernetes.


# kubectl deploy pod.yaml

API SERVER: It will decide to create a pod on which node. Receive the information when kubectl commands are executed………………………..
KUBE SCHEDULER: It will schedule the creation of pod on node based on the request from API Server.
ETCD: Store key values and cluster details as backup. While restart the cluster, these backup details are required. 
Controller: It use to monitor the pod status and ensure whether the desired state matches actual state on the auto healing. If replica set is 3 then 3 pods should be active.
Cloud Controller Manager: If a user wants to create load balancer, storage on Kubernetes. Then k8s needs to understand the cloud provider like AWS to create the request.

3. Life cycle of Kubernetes:  Install/Upgrade/Modify/Deletion of clusters.

4. POD deployment?
Kubernetes pod can be created using pod.yml file which has API version and specification
In a POD, Container A can access Container B. Since container A and B are in the same Kubernetes pod which is allowed to do shared networking which is in the local host and do the shared storage.
POD is basically a wrapper for container. 
Cluster IP will be allocated to Pod by kubeproxy
Application in the container can be accessed via cluster IP which is assigned by kubeproxy.
